⚙️ Day 07 — Linux Process & Service Management

Every application running in Linux is called a process.
DevOps Engineers constantly monitor, manage, stop, and restart processes & services on servers.

📌 What is a Process?

A process is a running instance of a program.

Examples:

🌐 Nginx Web Server
🐳 Docker
☸️ Kubernetes services
🗄️ Databases
📦 Background applications


🔍 1. ps — Process Status
📌 Definition

Displays currently running processes.

🛠️ Syntax
ps

✅ Example Output
PID TTY          TIME CMD
1200 pts/0    00:00:00 bash


🔥 Commonly Used Option

ps aux

📖 Meaning
| Option | Purpose              |
| ------ | -------------------- |
| `a`    | All users processes  |
| `u`    | User-oriented format |
| `x`    | Background processes |

✅ Example Output
root      1023  nginx
ubuntu    2045  python


⚡ 2. top — Real-Time Process Monitoring
📌 Definition

Displays:

CPU usage
Memory usage
Running processes
System load

in real-time.

🛠️ Syntax
top

🔴 Exit Top

Press:
q


💀 3. kill — Stop a Process
📌 Definition

Terminates a process using PID (Process ID).

🛠️ Syntax
kill PID

✅ Example
kill 2045

🔍 Find Process PID
ps aux

🚨 Force Kill Process
kill -9 PID

⚠️ Forcefully stops process immediately.

🔥 4. pkill — Kill by Process Name
📌 Definition

Kills process using process name.

🛠️ Syntax
pkill process_name

✅ Example
pkill nginx

🖥️ 5. systemctl — Service Management
📌 Definition

Used to manage system services.

Very important in modern Linux systems.

🛠️ Common Commands

▶️ Start Service
sudo systemctl start nginx

⏹️ Stop Service
sudo systemctl stop nginx

🔄 Restart Service
sudo systemctl restart nginx

📊 Check Service Status
sudo systemctl status nginx

🚀 Enable Service at Boot
sudo systemctl enable nginx

❌ Disable Service
sudo systemctl disable nginx


🧰 6. service — Legacy Service Management
📌 Definition

Older command for managing services.

Still used in some systems.

🛠️ Syntax
sudo service nginx status

✅ Example
sudo service nginx restart


🧪 Hands-On Practice

Run these commands:

ps aux

top

sudo systemctl status nginx


📂 Real DevOps Scenario

Install Nginx
sudo apt install nginx

▶️ Start Nginx
sudo systemctl start nginx

📊 Check Status
sudo systemctl status nginx

🌐 Verify Running Service
ss -tulnp

Look for:

:80

✅ Means web server is running successfully.

🔄 Restart Web Server
sudo systemctl restart nginx


💡 Why Process Management Matters?

DevOps Engineers frequently:

🔍 Monitor applications
🛠️ Restart failed services
🚨 Kill stuck processes
📊 Analyze server load
⚙️ Manage production services

🎯 Important Commands Summary
| Command     | Purpose                   |
| ----------- | ------------------------- |
| `ps`        | Show processes            |
| `ps aux`    | Detailed process list     |
| `top`       | Live monitoring           |
| `kill`      | Stop process using PID    |
| `pkill`     | Stop by process name      |
| `systemctl` | Manage services           |
| `service`   | Legacy service management |

💡 Key Learnings

✅ Every running application is a process
✅ ps aux displays all running processes
✅ top monitors system resources live
✅ kill stops unwanted processes
✅ systemctl manages Linux services
✅ Service management is critical in DevOps
